  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and regulations aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- 40 recommendations widely adopted by countries worldwide\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides framework for international cooperation against money laundering\n- Encourages asset seizure and international legal assistance\n\n3. Basel Committee's Core Principles\n- Banking supervision guidelines to prevent financial crimes\n\n4. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establishes regulatory requirements for financial institutions in EU countries\n\n5. Bank Secrecy Act (U.S.) and similar national laws\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate customer identification and record-keeping\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal control systems\n- Cooperate with law enforcement investigations\n\nMost developed countries have national laws aligned with these international standards to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing.",
